Note:
This file implements expression parsing for Runa language expressions.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Parse arithmetic, logical, and comparison expressions using Pratt parser
- Handle ternary operator parsing (condition ? true_value : false_value) - v0.0.8.5 feature
- Process function calls and method invocations
- Handle expression precedence and associativity
- Support string interpolation parsing (f"text {expr}") - v0.0.8.5 feature
- Parse range expressions and member access

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Expression parsing is fundamental to Runa's computational capabilities
- Pratt parser ensures correct precedence and associativity handling
- Ternary operator is a key v0.0.8.5 feature requirement
- String interpolation enables dynamic string construction
- Proper expression parsing enables correct evaluation and code generation

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Pratt parser implementation for expressions
- Ternary operator parsing and validation (v0.0.8.5)
- Function call and method invocation parsing
- String interpolation parsing (v0.0.8.5)
- Range expression and member access parsing
- Expression precedence and associativity handling

Dependencies:
- Imports parser.runa for parser state and token navigation
- Imports precedence.runa for operator precedence handling
- Imports ast_builder.runa for AST construction
- Imports lexical components for token recognition
- Imports memory/layout.runa for structure allocation
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/parsing/parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/parsing/precedence.runa" as Precedence
Import "compiler/frontend/parsing/ast_builder.runa" as ASTBuilder
Import "compiler/frontend/parsing/ast.runa" as AST
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrimitive
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/literals.runa" as Literals
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/keywords.runa" as Keywords
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/math_symbols.runa" as MathSymbols
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/operators.runa" as Operators
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/delimiters.runa" as Delimiters
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/token_constants.runa" as TokenConstants

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser-side token and context constants referenced by expression parsing.
Note: These mirror the lexical token codes (TOKEN_STRING -> string-literal class
Note: 100; TOKEN_EQUALS -> the '=' assignment token 600; the formatted/interpolated
Note: string tokens -> 102) and extend the parser's parsing-context enum with the
Note: argument-list / element-list contexts the error detector inspects.
Note: ============================================================================
Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: Token-type constants — values EXACTLY mirror the authoritative lexer emit
Note: values. String/numeric/character literals arrive from the literal tokenizer
Note: (literals.runa 100-114, 140). Boolean and null/none/nil arrive as KEYWORDS
Note: (keywords.runa True 410 / False 411 / Null 420 / None 421 / Nil 422) because
Note: the lexer registers them in the keyword table — the literal-class boolean/null
Note: codes (120-132) are never emitted, so the parser must match the keyword codes.
Note: Identifier is the lexer.runa value 150 (distinct from the delimiter 200-210
Note: range — resolves the historical TOKEN_IDENTIFIER/TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN=200 collision).
Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: String / formatted-string literal classes (literals.runa)
Note: Numeric literal classes (literals.runa)
Note: Boolean / null literals arrive as KEYWORDS (keywords.runa values)
Note: Identifier (lexer.runa)
Note: Lexer special tokens (lexer.runa)
Note: Delimiters (delimiters.runa)
Note: Operators (operators.runa)
Note: Keywords (keywords.runa)
Note: Pipeline / aggregation keywords (keywords.runa)
Constant CONTEXT_ARGUMENT_LIST as Integer is 6       Note: Inside a call argument list
Constant CONTEXT_ELEMENT_LIST as Integer is 7        Note: Inside a collection element list

Note: Precedence level of canonical "is ..." comparison phrases. Mirrors
Note: precedence.runa PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON (7) so the Pratt loop honours
Note: min_precedence when deciding whether to consume an "is" comparison.
Constant PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON_LEVEL as Integer is 7

Note: Precedence level of symbolic comparison operators (<, >, <=, >=). Mirrors
Note: precedence.runa PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON (7). Used by the with-call argument
Note: exclusion so a bare comparison terminates an argument rather than being
Note: absorbed into it.
Constant PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON_OP as Integer is 7

Note: Precedence level of symbolic equality operators (==, !=). Mirrors
Note: precedence.runa PRECEDENCE_EQUALITY (6). Used by the with-call argument
Note: exclusion so a bare equality test terminates an argument.
Constant PRECEDENCE_EQUALITY_OP as Integer is 6

Note: Minimum precedence used when parsing a single argument inside a
Note: canonical "with"-call argument clause. Mirrors precedence.runa
Note: PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_OR (3): it sits ABOVE logical-or (1) and logical-and
Note: (2) so the canonical "and" separator between arguments
Note: (`add with 20 and 22`) terminates the per-argument Pratt parse instead of
Note: being absorbed as a boolean operator, while still allowing bitwise (3-5),
Note: shift, additive and multiplicative operators to compose freely within one
Note: argument (`helper with a plus b`, `with r_bytes, m3 bitwise_and 15`).
Note: Comparison (7) and equality (6), though numerically above this floor, are
Note: explicitly terminated by the with-argument context exclusions below so a
Note: bare `helper with x is less than y` binds the comparison OUTSIDE the call,
Note: matching the stage1 monolith's arg chain (which skips both tiers). An
Note: argument that genuinely needs a top-level comparison, equality, or logical
Note: "and"/"or" must be parenthesised, matching the stage1 grammar's
Note: arg-context operator hierarchy.
Constant PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL as Integer is 3

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Parsing Entry Points
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Parse an expression using Pratt parser algorithm
    
    Parameters:
      parser - Pointer to ParserState
   
    Returns:
      Pointer to expression AST node
      Returns 0 on parsing error
   
    Algorithm:
    1. Parse left operand using parse_primary_expression
    2. While current token is binary operator with precedence > 0:
       - Get operator precedence using Precedence.get_operator_precedence
       - If precedence > 0 (not ternary), parse binary expression
       - Otherwise, break (ternary handled separately)
    3. Check for ternary operator (? :)
    4. If ternary found, parse ternary expression
    5. Return final expression AST node
    :End Note
    
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse with minimum precedence of 0 (parse everything)
    Let expression be proc parse_expression_with_precedence with parser, 0

    If expression is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check for ternary operator (? :) which has special handling
    Let current_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    Let token_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

    Note: If question mark found, parse ternary expression
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_QUESTION_MARK:
        Let ternary be proc parse_ternary_expression with parser, expression
        Return ternary
    End If

    Return expression
End Process

Process called "parse_expression_with_precedence" takes parser as Integer, min_precedence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Parse expression with minimum precedence constraint (Pratt parser core)
    
    Parameters:
      parser - Pointer to ParserState
      min_precedence - Minimum precedence level to parse
    
    Returns:
      Pointer to expression AST node
      Returns 0 on parsing error
    
    Pratt parser algorithm:
    1. Parse left operand using parse_primary_expression
    2. While current token is binary operator:
       - Get operator precedence
       - If precedence < min_precedence, break
       - If precedence == min_precedence and not left-associative, break
       - Parse binary expression with precedence + 1
    3. Return expression AST node
    :End Note

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse left operand (prefix expression or primary)
    Let current_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    Let token_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

    Note: Check for unary operators (prefix)
    Let is_unary be proc is_unary_operator from Precedence with token_type
    If is_unary is equal to 1:
        Let left be proc parse_unary_expression with parser
    Otherwise:
        Set left to proc parse_primary_expression with parser
    End If

    If left is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse binary operators with Pratt precedence climbing
    Loop forever:
        Set current_token to proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
        Set token_type to proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

        Note:
        Canonical comparison phrases begin with the particle "is" (TOKEN_IS),
        which the lexer emits as a standalone token and which is therefore NOT
        registered as a binary operator in the precedence table. Handle the full
        "is [not] {equal to | greater than [or equal to] | less than [or equal
        to] | within ...}" phrase here so the Pratt loop does not stop at "is"
        and silently truncate the condition (which previously dropped every
        If/While/For whose condition used a comparison). Comparison binds at
        PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON; respect the caller's min_precedence so chained
        operators associate correctly.
        :End Note
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IS:
            If PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON_LEVEL is less than min_precedence:
                Break
            End If
            Note:
            With-call argument context exclusion. A canonical "with"-call
            argument is parsed at PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL so the "and"/","
            separators (logical level) terminate each argument while bitwise (3-5),
            shift (8), additive (9) and multiplicative (10) operators still compose
            inside one argument. Comparison (7) and equality (6) sit ABOVE the
            bitwise floor numerically, so a plain min_precedence floor would let
            `proc f from M with x, "ARC" is equal to 1` absorb the `is equal to 1`
            into the final argument and silently drop the enclosing comparison —
            leaving the If/While condition as the bare call (which then fails
            "Condition must be Boolean" in HIR lowering). The stage1 monolith's
            arg-context operator chain bottoms out ABOVE comparison/equality
            (parser_parse_arg_bit_and recurses straight into shift, skipping the
            comparison and equality tiers), so a comparison written without
            parentheses binds OUTSIDE the call. Mirror that here: when parsing a
            with-call argument, never consume a canonical "is ..." comparison.
            :End Note
            If min_precedence is equal to PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL:
                Break
            End If
            Set left to proc parse_is_comparison with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check if current token is a binary operator
        Let is_binary be proc is_binary_operator from Precedence with token_type
        If is_binary is equal to 0:
            Break  Note: Not a binary operator, done parsing
        End If

        Note: Get operator precedence
        Let precedence be proc get_operator_precedence from Precedence with token_type

        Note: If precedence less than minimum, stop parsing
        If precedence is less than min_precedence:
            Break
        End If

        Note:
        With-call argument context exclusion (symbolic comparison/equality).
        The bitwise tiers (3-5) must keep composing inside a with-argument
        (123 self-host sites use forms like `with r_bytes, 3, m3 bitwise_and 15`),
        so the floor stays at PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL (3) rather than
        being raised above comparison. That floor admits bitwise but, being
        below comparison/equality numerically, would also admit the symbolic
        `==`/`!=` (PRECEDENCE_EQUALITY, 6) and `<`/`>`/`<=`/`>=`
        (PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON, 7) operators. Those must NOT bind inside an
        argument (matching the monolith's arg chain, which skips both tiers),
        so terminate the argument when one is seen at the with-argument floor.
        :End Note
        If min_precedence is equal to PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL:
            If precedence is equal to PRECEDENCE_EQUALITY_OP:
                Break
            End If
            If precedence is equal to PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON_OP:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        Note: Check associativity for equal precedence
        If precedence is equal to min_precedence:
            Let assoc be proc get_operator_associativity from Precedence with token_type
            Note: If right-associative (assoc = 1), stop parsing
            If assoc is equal to 1:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        Note: Parse binary expression with this operator
        Set left to proc parse_binary_expression with parser, left, token_type
        If left is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End While

    Note: Check for postfix operators (member access, function call, indexing)
    Loop forever:
        Set current_token to proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
        Set token_type to proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

        Note: Check for member access (.)
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DOT:
            Set left to proc parse_member_expression with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check for function call (()
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
            Set left to proc parse_call_expression with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check for canonical named-call argument clause (`callee with arg
        Note: [and arg] [, arg] ...`). This is the primary Runa call surface
        Note: form: `helper with 41`, `add with 20 and 22`. The opening "with"
        Note: promotes the parsed callee expression into a function call whose
        Note: arguments follow. Handled as a postfix operator so chained forms
        Note: (`obj.method with x`) and qualified callees compose naturally.
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WITH:
            Set left to proc parse_with_call_arguments with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check for array indexing ([])
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
            Set left to proc parse_index_expression with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check for range operator (..)
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_RANGE:
            Set left to proc parse_range_expression with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check for "sorted by" operator (Language Additions v0.0.8.5)
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SORTED:
            Set left to proc parse_sorted_expression with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: No more postfix operators, done
        Break
    End While

    Return left
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DEC-0018 Layer 3 — Contextual Aggregation Disambiguation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "is_expression_head" takes token_kind as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Fixed token-class membership test: does token_kind begin a primary
    expression operand? This is the bounded, scope-free predicate DEC-0018
    Layer 3 uses to decide whether a bare aggregation word reads as the
    aggregation OPERATOR. It mirrors EXACTLY the set of token kinds that
    parse_primary_expression (and the unary-prefix arm of the Pratt loop)
    accept as the first token of an operand. It performs no source rescan
    and consults no scope — it is a constant-time discriminant test.

    The expression-head class is:
      - Literals: string/raw/formatted-string (100-102), numeric (110-114),
        boolean (120-121), null/none/nil (130-132), character (140).
      - Identifier (150).
      - Grouping / collection openers: '(' (200), '[' (204).
      - f-string prefix (102, already covered by formatted-string).
      - Pipeline / selection / aggregation keyword expression-starters:
        Filter (329), the five aggregation words (335-339), first/last
        (345/346), Group (349), Transform (357).
      - Function-pointer '$' (654) and indirect-call 'proc' (440).
      - Any unary prefix operator (not / negative / positive / bitwise-not),
        delegated to Precedence.is_unary_operator.

    Returns 1 if token_kind can begin an expression operand, 0 otherwise.
    :End Note

    Note: Literals
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_RAW_STRING_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_FORMATTED_STRING_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_FLOAT_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_HEX_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_BINARY_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_OCTAL_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_BOOLEAN_TRUE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_BOOLEAN_FALSE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_NULL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_NONE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_NIL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_CHARACTER_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Identifier
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Grouping / collection openers
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_F_STRING:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Pipeline / selection / aggregation keyword expression-starters
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_FILTER:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_AVERAGE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_SUM:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_COUNT:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_MINIMUM:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_MAXIMUM:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_FIRST:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_LAST:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_GROUP:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_TRANSFORM:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Function-pointer and indirect-call openers
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_DOLLAR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_PROC:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Unary prefix operators (delegated to the precedence table so the two
    Note: recognition paths never diverge).
    Let unary_head be proc is_unary_operator from Precedence with token_kind
    If unary_head is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "aggregation_word_is_operator" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    DEC-0018 Layer 3 two-token gate. The current token is one of the five
    aggregation words (already known by the caller). This decides whether it
    reads as the aggregation OPERATOR or as a bare identifier.

    Rule (scope-free, O(1), bounded 2-token lookahead, no source rescan):
      operator iff  peek(1) is TOKEN_OF  AND  is_expression_head(peek(2)).

    Otherwise the word is an identifier. This is exactly why bare single-word
    `count` / `sum` used as identifiers keep working everywhere they are not
    followed by `of <expr>`.

    Returns 1 if the aggregation word should parse as the operator, 0 if it
    should be demoted to an identifier.
    :End Note

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let next_token be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 1
    If next_token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let next_kind be proc token_get_type from Parser with next_token
    If next_kind is not equal to TOKEN_OF:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let after_of_token be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 2
    If after_of_token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let after_of_kind be proc token_get_type from Parser with after_of_token
    Return proc is_expression_head with after_of_kind
End Process

Process called "demote_aggregation_to_identifier" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    DEC-0018 Layer 3 fallback. An aggregation word that the two-token gate
    did NOT classify as the operator is a plain identifier. The lexer stores
    the word's spelling in the token's value field (offset 8) even for hard
    keyword tokens, so the identifier name is read directly from the current
    token. One AST identifier node is built and the single token consumed —
    no source rescan, no extra allocation beyond the AST node itself.

    Returns the identifier AST node, or 0 on error.
    :End Note

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    If current_token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_value be proc token_get_value from Parser with current_token
    If token_value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with current_token
    Let token_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with current_token

    Let identifier_node be proc build_identifier_node from ASTBuilder with token_value, token_line, token_column
    If identifier_node is equal to 0:
        proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create identifier AST node for aggregation word used as identifier", token_line, token_column
        Return 0
    End If

    proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
    Return identifier_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Primary Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "parse_primary_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Parse a primary expression (literal, identifier, parenthesized)
    
    Parameters:
      parser - Pointer to ParserState
    
    Returns:
      Pointer to primary expression AST node
      Returns 0 on parsing error
    
    Primary expressions:
      - Literals: strings, numbers, booleans, null
      - Identifiers: variables, functions, types
      - Parenthesized: (expression)
      - String interpolation: f"text {expr}" (v0.0.8.5)
      - Array literals: [expr1, expr2, ...]
      - Tuple literals: (expr1, expr2, ...)
    
    Algorithm:
    1. Check current token type
    2. If literal: call parse_literal_expression
    3. If identifier: call parse_identifier_expression
    4. If left parenthesis: call parse_parenthesized_expression
    5. If string with f prefix: call parse_interpolated_string
    6. If left bracket: call parse_array_literal
    7. Otherwise: report error and return 0
    :End Note

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    Let token_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

    Note: Check for literals (string, number, boolean, null, character).
    Note: The literal token-type constants form the lexical literal class:
    Note:   string 100-102, numeric 110-114, boolean 120-121, null/none/nil 130-132, character 140.
    Let is_literal be 0
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_RAW_STRING_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FORMATTED_STRING_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FLOAT_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_HEX_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BINARY_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_OCTAL_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BOOLEAN_TRUE:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BOOLEAN_FALSE:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NULL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NONE:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NIL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_CHARACTER_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If is_literal is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_literal_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for canonical collection literal. Two surface forms reach the parser as
    Note: the SAME canonical token shape:
    Note:   - Source canonical "a list containing e1, e2, ...": article and "list" lex as
    Note:     identifiers, "containing" as TOKEN_CONTAINING (keyword table).
    Note:   - Bracketed "[e1, e2, ...]": the syntax transformer rewrites it to the token
    Note:     sequence a / list / containing / elements, BUT synthesises "containing" as a
    Note:     plain identifier (create_identifier_token), not the keyword token.
    Note:   - Empty "[]": transformer rewrites to "an empty list" (three identifiers, no
    Note:     "containing").
    Note: The article ("a"/"an") and "list"/"empty" all lex as TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, so this
    Note: is detected by token-value lookahead before the generic identifier branch.
    Note: "containing" is accepted as TOKEN_CONTAINING OR an identifier valued "containing"
    Note: so both the source and the transformed bracket form route here. Only the list
    Note: form lowers end-to-end today; dictionary/set literals have no HIR lowering and
    Note: are intentionally not intercepted (they would otherwise produce dropped output).
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Let cl_is_article be proc primary_token_value_is with current_token, "a"
        If cl_is_article is equal to 0:
            Set cl_is_article to proc primary_token_value_is with current_token, "an"
        End If
        If cl_is_article is equal to 1:
            Let cl_next be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 1

            Note: Empty-list form: "an empty list".
            Let cl_next_is_empty be proc primary_token_value_is with cl_next, "empty"
            If cl_next_is_empty is equal to 1:
                Let cl_after_empty be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 2
                Let cl_after_empty_is_list be proc primary_token_value_is with cl_after_empty, "list"
                If cl_after_empty_is_list is equal to 1:
                    Return proc parse_canonical_empty_list_literal with parser
                End If
            End If

            Note: Non-empty list form: "a list containing ...".
            Let cl_next_is_list be proc primary_token_value_is with cl_next, "list"
            If cl_next_is_list is equal to 1:
                Let cl_after be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 2
                Let cl_after_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with cl_after
                Let cl_after_is_containing be 0
                If cl_after_type is equal to TOKEN_CONTAINING:
                    Set cl_after_is_containing to 1
                End If
                If cl_after_is_containing is equal to 0:
                    Set cl_after_is_containing to proc primary_token_value_is with cl_after, "containing"
                End If
                If cl_after_is_containing is equal to 1:
                    Return proc parse_canonical_list_literal with parser
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for identifier
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Return proc parse_identifier_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for left parenthesis (parenthesized expression or tuple)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
        Return proc parse_parenthesized_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for left bracket (array literal)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
        Return proc parse_array_literal with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for f-string prefix (string interpolation)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_F_STRING:
        Return proc parse_interpolated_string with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for Filter keyword (Language Additions v0.0.8.5)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FILTER:
        Return proc parse_filter_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for aggregation keywords (Language Additions v0.0.8.5).
    Note: DEC-0018 Layer 3: each aggregation word reads as the aggregation
    Note: OPERATOR only when the two-token gate (next token is `of` AND the
    Note: token after `of` begins an expression) holds; otherwise it is a bare
    Note: identifier and is demoted. This is scope-free, O(1), no source rescan.
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AVERAGE:
        Let avg_is_operator be proc aggregation_word_is_operator with parser
        If avg_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_aggregation_expression with parser, TOKEN_AVERAGE
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SUM:
        Let sum_is_operator be proc aggregation_word_is_operator with parser
        If sum_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_aggregation_expression with parser, TOKEN_SUM
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_COUNT:
        Let count_is_operator be proc aggregation_word_is_operator with parser
        If count_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_aggregation_expression with parser, TOKEN_COUNT
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MINIMUM:
        Let min_is_operator be proc aggregation_word_is_operator with parser
        If min_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_aggregation_expression with parser, TOKEN_MINIMUM
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MAXIMUM:
        Let max_is_operator be proc aggregation_word_is_operator with parser
        If max_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_aggregation_expression with parser, TOKEN_MAXIMUM
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for first/last selection keywords (Language Additions v0.0.8.5)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FIRST:
        Return proc parse_first_last_expression with parser, TOKEN_FIRST
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LAST:
        Return proc parse_first_last_expression with parser, TOKEN_LAST
    End If

    Note: Check for Group keyword (Language Additions v0.0.8.5)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GROUP:
        Return proc parse_group_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for Transform keyword (Language Additions v0.0.8.5)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TRANSFORM:
        Return proc parse_transform_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for $ (function pointer creation)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DOLLAR:
        Return proc parse_function_pointer_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for proc (indirect function call)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PROC:
        Return proc parse_proc_call_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Unexpected token - report error
    proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected primary expression (literal, identifier, or parenthesized expression)", proc token_get_line from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser, proc token_get_column from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    Return 0
End Process

